Kingdom","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Anglie"},"da":{"–":"Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1527–1600":"1527–1600","–Male":"Afdød","1600":"1600","4 May 1541":"4. maj 1541","1527":"1527","St. Mildred Poultry's Church, London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England"},"nl":{"–":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1527–1600":"1527–1600","–Male":"Overleden","1600":"1600","4 May 1541":"4 mei 1541","1527":"1527","St. Mildred Poultry's Church, London, England":"London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1527–1600":"1527–1600","–Male":"Deceased","1600":"1600","4 May 1541":"4 May 1541","1527":"1527","St. Mildred Poultry's Church, London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Panstone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from Fauntstone in Shaugh (Devon). The place probably takes its name from the surname <i>Faunt</i> (genitive <i>Fauntes</i>) + Middle English <i>toun</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, meaning ‘farmstead of the <i>Faunt</i> family’ and probably to be associated with the family of Samson <i>le Enfaunt</i>, a juror of Plympton Hundred in Devon in 1249. For the surname <i>Faunt</i>, see   Fant  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fant","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>infaunt(e)</i> ‘baby, child’ (Old French <i>enfant</i>), hence a nickname for someone of a childish (or childlike) disposition. This name arose when, in medieval England, Anglo-Norman French <i>l'enfant</i> was wrongly understood as <i>le fant</i>.","Italian (Veneto): variant of   Infante  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Panstone married Alis Clarke on 4 May 1541, in London, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1527–1600":"1527–1600","–Male":"Surnud","1600":"1600","4 May 1541":"4. mai 1541","1527":"1527","St. Mildred Poultry's Church, London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1527–1600":"1527–1600","–Male":"Kuollut","1600":"1600","4 May 1541":"4. toukokuuta 1541","1527":"1527","St. Mildred Poultry's Church, London, England":"London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1527–1600":"1527–1600","–Male":"Décédé","1600":"1600","4 May 1541":"4 mai 1541","1527":"1527","St. Mildred Poultry's Church, London, England":"Londres, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Panstone a épousé Alis Clarke le 4 mai 1541, à Londres, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1527–1600":"1527–1600","–Male":"Verstorben","1600":"160